Paul Herman, News24Minister of Finance Pravin Gordhan (Netwerk24) Multimedia &nbsp; &nbsp; User Galleries &nbsp; &nbsp; News in Pictures Send us your pictures &nbsp; &nbsp; Send us your stories A large group of National Treasury staff sang the anti-apartheid song Senzenina (what have we done?) as axed finance minister Pravin Gordhan, his former deputy Mcebisi Jonas and director-general Lungisa Fuzile entered the head office of the finance department for the last time.WATCHCape Town - While they may not agree with President Jacob Zuma's choices, the African National Congress must still rally behind new and old Cabinet ministers, party deputy secretary general Jessie Duarte said on Friday."Congratulations to all the new ministers appointed by the President. Ministers who lost their portfolios cannot be seen as being lost to ANC," Duarte tweeted on Friday."We may not agree with the President on the choices he has made, but ours is to rally behind these ministers and support them."She was reacting to Zuma's dramatic late night Cabinet reshuffle, which saw 20 ANC MPs given new positions and five ministers "released".Finance Minister Pravin Gordhan and his deputy Mcebisi Jonas were among these five. Home Affairs Minister Malusi Gigaba will replace Gordhan."We expect Malusi Gigaba to understand that National Treasury is the citadel of our economy and will safeguard it from any looting and corruption!"ANC chief whip Jackson Mthembu said he did not agree with the decision to axe Gordhan and Jonas based on a "suspect" intelligence report."Their commitment to the NDR [national democratic revolution] is unquestionable," he tweeted.The Democratic Alliance said it would seek a court interdict to stop Zuma from swearing in his new ministers and deputy ministers at 18:00 on Friday."We have asked our legal team to stop Zuma from swearing in the new ministers," DA leader Mmusi Maimane told reporters at OR Tambo International Airport.He called on all South Africans to march to ANC headquarters Luthuli House and said all parties, and members of the ANC, needed to support a call of no confidence in Zuma. 24.com encourages commentary submitted via MyNews24. Contributions of 200 words or more will be considered for publication.